\begin_layout Section
\noindent
Benefit and relevance to INCF mission
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align block
As mentioned in the INCF mission statement, neuroinformatics poses a specific
 challenge for training, as the variety of knowledge and research cultures
 comprising neuroinformatics is only rarely combined in one single place
 and often falls at the boundaries of traditional academic departments.
 The training we propose will draw on the combined experience and knowledge
 of several different neuroinformatics practitioners and provides one of
 these rare opportunities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align block
The list of instructors proposed embodies the spirit of international cooperatio
n, which underlies the mission of the INCF, with instructors from the US,
 from France, from Switzerland, from Germany and from the UK.
 We intend for the student population to embody this spirit, at least in
 part, by inviting international participants to apply for travel grants,
 which will cover the expenses of 5 such students.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align block
Among the three components of neuroinformatics (tools, models and data-bases),
 this course is aimed mostly at tool-development and data analysis.
 However, other topics such as data-base and data-sharing will be discussed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align block
Of the core competencies defined in the summary of the 1st INCF Workshop
 on Needs for Training in Neuroinformatics held in Edinburgh in July 23-25,
 2008 (page 6), this course will thoroughly address the following three:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\noindent
\align block
“Knowledge of stochastic modeling, time-series analysis, exploratory data
 analysis and applied statistics”.
 These topics are extremely relevant for neuroimaging and will be covered
 both at the theoretical level, as well as at the practical level.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\noindent
\align block
“Ability to programme in high-level languages”.
 Although we expect many of the participants to have at least some knowledge
 of programming, one of the the major goals of the course is to increase
 participants’ confidence in their programming skills to a degree where
 they will be able to publicly share the code they use for their analysis,
 making their analysis reproducible by others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\noindent
\align block
“Knowledge of imaging techniques and image analysis”: This topic is also
 central to the course an will be covered extensively, both at the theoretical
 level and at the practical level.
\end_layout

